  :outline
"# Book of Introspection — 16 chapters, 8 appendices

The book teaches Motoi programmers how to look inside their own programs. Every chapter answers one question with runnable verbs. Every chapter builds on the last. By the end the reader can hand-write a REPL meta-command, walk a macro expansion, read an error record's fields, and ask a peer LLM verb to explain a value they don't understand.

## Chapter 1 — What is introspection: programs that can look inside themselves

Introspection is the language's willingness to answer questions about itself. A program that only computes is a black box; a program that also describes what it computes is a workshop with a window. This chapter defines introspection in Motoi terms, introduces the seven surfaces the book will walk through (verb metadata, describe, doc, env, macro, reader, cortex), and shows the first two verbs a reader can type: `(help 'car)` and `(describe 'map)`. It ends with a promise — everything in this book is a verb; there is no privileged tooling.

## Chapter 2 — Verb metadata: the shape of every verb

Every verb in Motoi carries the same record. Name, arity, contract, doc, examples, source, namespace, tier, perm, since. This chapter walks each field, explains what it means at runtime, and shows how the field is written when a verb is registered. Readers learn to read a verb record the way a hardware engineer reads a datasheet: pick the field you need, ignore the rest, come back later. The chapter ends with a table of every field, its type, its default, and its intended reader.

## Chapter 3 — Describe + typeOf: what am I looking at?

`describe` gives you a one-paragraph human-readable summary of a verb. `type-of` and `typeOf` give you the value-side answer: what runtime shape do I actually have in my hand? This chapter separates the two — description versus mechanical type — and shows how they compose. Readers learn to answer three questions with two verbs: what is this named thing, what is this in-my-hand thing, and how are they related.

## Chapter 4 — docOf + sourceOf + examples: where does this verb live?

A verb has a docstring. It has a source location. It has tiered examples — novice, intermediate, expert. This chapter shows how to reach each of them from Scheme and from the REPL meta-command layer. Readers learn that the reference manual is not a separate document; it is the sum of `(doc-of ...)` and `(source-of ...)` and `(examples-of ...)` for every registered verb. This is the payoff for the reader — one place, one shape, always accessible.

## Chapter 5 — Environments and bindings: what does the program know right now?

An environment is a chain of frames. Each frame is a set of name-to-value bindings. This chapter shows how to enumerate the bindings in the current env, how to see what the parent env holds, how to introspect a closure's captured bindings, and how to distinguish a define at the top level from a let-binding buried in a lambda body. Readers learn that Scheme's lexical scope is not magic — it is a walkable data structure, and Motoi lets them walk it.

## Chapter 6 — Macros and macroexpand: the code before the code

A macro rewrites source before evaluation. If you cannot see the rewrite you cannot debug it. This chapter shows `,expand` in the REPL, `macroexpand` as a verb, and `macroexpand-1` for a single step. Readers learn to compare their intent (the macro use) to the actual generated code (the expansion) and to spot the classic macro bugs — unwanted capture, missing gensym, wrong ellipsis handling — by reading the expansion.

## Chapter 7 — The reader: how source becomes forms

Between a string of characters and a callable form there is the reader. This chapter shows how Motoi tokenizes, parses, and hands off to the expander. Readers learn to call the reader directly on a string, see the resulting form, and inspect the source-position metadata that follows a form through evaluation. This is the layer under macros and the layer under everything else.

## Chapter 8 — Errors as data: introspecting failure

An error in Motoi is a record with fields. This chapter enumerates the fields, shows how to bind the last-raised error, and demonstrates how the error record composes with the LLM-augmented `fix` and `pretty-error` verbs. Readers learn to stop reading errors as strings and start reading them as data structures they can query.

## Chapter 9 — Trace and watch: introspection over time

Sometimes a single snapshot is not enough. `,trace` records every call to a verb; `,watch` re-evaluates an expression on every prompt; the trace log itself is a value you can query. This chapter shows how to enable them, how to read their output, and how to turn a trace back into a story the programmer can understand.

## Chapter 10 — Cortex: introspecting what the program remembers

Cortex is Motoi's persistent memory graph. `cortex/query` is an introspection verb on the graph itself. This chapter shows how to enumerate what the program has recorded, how to filter by subject or predicate or source, and how to read a value's provenance chain back to its origin. Composes with Book of Jesse Ch 13 — this chapter is the introspection lens on the memory Ch 13 introduced.

## Chapter 11 — The registry: introspecting the whole vocabulary

Every registered verb is in one map. `snapshot-registry` returns that map as data. This chapter shows how to iterate the registry, how to filter by namespace or tier or perm, and how to build small tools that summarize the language for a reader (a namespace map, a permission audit, a since-tag report). Readers learn that the language surface is itself queryable.

## Chapter 12 — Apropos and search: introspecting by shape

`,apropos` matches verb names by regex. `find-by-arity`, `find-by-contract`, `find-by-example` extend that to shape-based search. This chapter shows how a reader who does not remember a verb name can still find it — by describing what it does or by giving a sample call. Readers learn that the fastest search over the language is regex against names plus type-shape narrowing.

## Chapter 13 — Ask the LLM: introspection through a peer

When mechanical introspection ends, a peer verb begins. This chapter introduces `what-is`, `explain`, `shape-of`, `reason-about`, `who-uses`, and the LLM-augmented family that grounds itself in the registry and Cortex before it answers. Readers learn that the LLM does not replace introspection — it augments it, and it is honest about the difference between what the registry says (grounded) and what the LLM guesses (labelled with :confidence). Feeds from engineering/LLM-AUGMENTED-REPL-1.0.

## Chapter 14 — Composer introspection: widget round-trip is introspection too

A composer canvas is a live introspection of a form. Move a slider, the form updates. Edit the form, the widget follows. This chapter shows `composer/emit` (canvas to form) and `composer/apply` (form to canvas) as an introspection pair — the widgets are a rendering of the form's shape, and the widgets can be interrogated the same way any verb record can be. Feeds from engineering/COMPOSER-1.0.

## Chapter 15 — Performance introspection: time, fuel, memory

Motoi programs run under a fuel budget. `,time` reports wall time; the fuel counter reports how much of the budget was spent; memory reporting shows allocation shape. This chapter teaches readers to measure before they optimize, to read the fuel report as a proxy for computational cost, and to build simple benchmarks that survive across runtimes.

## Chapter 16 — Safe introspection: perm, sandbox, and what shouldn't leak

Not all introspection is safe. Reading a verb's perm tier is safe; reading a secret env variable is not. This chapter shows the sandbox boundary — what the registry exposes, what it does not, what a runtime redacts before returning a record, and how a cart author can mark a value as never-introspectable. The book closes on the honesty principle: introspection is a superpower, and Motoi trusts the programmer to use it without leaking through it.

## Appendices

A — Reference-manual anatomy: the SLAT schema of a verb record, field by field, with types and defaults.
B — Introspection cheat-sheet: one entry per introspection verb, printable.
C — Building a `,help` command from scratch: a 40-line REPL extension that demonstrates every verb the book covered.
D — Introspection at the boundary: foreign values, sidecars, sockets, and how to describe values you did not create.
E — Reader-time introspection: source positions, comment attachment, meta-programming from the reader layer.
F — Introspection for teachers: pedagogical patterns for using introspection to unstick a learner.
G — Introspection for debuggers: practical bug-hunting recipes built entirely from introspection verbs.
H — Composer-in-book: an interactive composer demonstration that uses the round-trip as the teaching device."

  :status "wave-1-outline-frozen-2026-07-17")
